<div id="review_1416808983" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1416808983" />
    <a title="Brooke Waite" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/850609-brooke-waite"><img alt="Brooke Waite" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1418667474p2/850609.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1416808983?book_show_action=true">Oct 14, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brooke Waite" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brooke Waite" href="/user/show/850609-brooke-waite">Brooke Waite</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/850609-brooke-waite?shelf=2106-favorites">2106-favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1416808983" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4982338502736098533">My review could never do justice to this incredible book! I learned so much, cried so much and felt the deep agony of family, love, art, tradition and memories ravaged by the horrors of war. Part love story (sometimes a little overly precious) part war saga, the reader travels from luscious light-filled Paris with its promise of future to the strangled dread and terror of Budapest. I hadn&apos;t learned about the fate of the Hungarian people as Allies of the Reich, but more especially their Jewish po</span>
  <span id="freeText4982338502736098533" style="display:none">My review could never do justice to this incredible book! I learned so much, cried so much and felt the deep agony of family, love, art, tradition and memories ravaged by the horrors of war. Part love story (sometimes a little overly precious) part war saga, the reader travels from luscious light-filled Paris with its promise of future to the strangled dread and terror of Budapest. I hadn't learned about the fate of the Hungarian people as Allies of the Reich, but more especially their Jewish population and their fate which you can only imagine was as terrible as the fate of Jews in other parts of Europe. I had every possible emotion and reaction to this book. My heart broke over and over again.<br /><br />One thing I will mention as a possible critique is that every main character seemed to have no ill-intented bone in their bodies. Every character that was good was ever self-sacrificing, strong and unwavering in times of peril and only displayed qualities that every person on earth would love to possess. There were 'bad' or evil characters because every story needs a vice or two. The story is based on the authors own decendants and if that is her desire to portray them that way who am I to judge :) Regardless, an impressive, emotional roller coaster of a ride!</span>
  <a data-text-id="4982338502736098533" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


